==Speculation==

The spread of the 'seven sage' legend westwards during the 1st and 2nd millennia has been speculated to have led to the creation of the tale of the [[Nephilim]] (Genesis 6:1-4) as recounted in the [[Old Testament]],{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|loc = "Apkallu", p.74, col.1}}{{sfn|Conrad|Newing|1987|loc= ''The Mespotamian Counterparts of the Biblical Nepilim'' A. Draffkorn Kilner, pp.39- }} and may have an echo in the text of the [[Book of Proverbs]] (Prov 9:1): ''"Wisdom built her house. She set out its seven pillars."'' The story of [[Enoch (ancestor of Noah)|Enoch]] ("seventh from Adam") and his ascension to heaven has also been proposed to be a variant or influenced by the seventh apkallu Utuabzu who is also said to have ascended to heaven in the ''[[bit meseri]]''.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|loc = "Apkallu", p.74, col.1}}

==Misconceptions==
Oannes was once conjectured to be a form or another name of the ancient Babylonian god [[Ea (Babylonian god)|Ea]].<ref>{{citation| last = Sayce| first = Archibald H.| authorlink=Archibald Sayce |year =1898|pages = 232, 368–9, 391|  work = The Hibbert Lectures| title = Lectures on the Origin and Growth of Religion as illustrated by the Religion of the Ancient Babylonians| publisher =  Wiliams & Norgate| edition = 5th }}</ref> It is now thought that the name is the Greek form of the Babylonian ''Uanna'', an Apkallu.{{sfn|van der Toorn|Becking|van der Horst|1999|loc = "Apkallu", p.72}}

